Restoring the very American ideal that labour rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill to protect union organizing as a civil right.
“Based on how unions work, middle-class jobs work,” says Ellison, a Democratic senator from Minnesota who is co-chair of the Congressional committee.
That's why I'm so proud to introduce an Employee Empowerment Act along with John Lewis' pattern of occasional rights.
This ground-breaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination when organizing in trade unions as other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces
Adjusting the Labor Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination to join unions, to stand trial in civil court - and to sue for compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents are proposing in the bill is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite trade-union struggles in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to adopt, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember it, when the country in one breath championed democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of assembly.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toja's military autocracy would be replaced by democracy.
They were convinced that employees and their unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, included language, and openly recognized that "the right of employees to assemble, to bargain collectively, and to act is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Realizing that employees would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that openly states: “The right to form associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or profession.
Arrangements that will limit this right or seek to damage it will be revoked. Measures to fulfill such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a global treaty in 1948, the draftsmen and Roosevelt included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form and join unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to build a civil and democratic society, Americans explained that the right to form labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that trade unions have not diminished the strength of a nation, but have expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an unsuspected level.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History never forgets and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis restore the ideals that have lifted America and made it a true promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily blocks bill that could shut down all Louisiana abortion clinics
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that lawyers say would likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
The ordinance, signed by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June, would require abortion doctors to have the right to admit a patient to a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge’s ruling means that doctors can temporarily continue to perform legal abortions and must obtain permission in the meantime.
“The proposing party will be able to legally conduct its business and in the meantime, it will obtain a permit,” federal judge John deGravelles said in a statement.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month so that the judge can make a more permanent ruling on the law.
Abortion rights activists welcomed the resolution, which is the latest in a series of similar measures, and said it would give doctors more time to get permission.
“Today’s decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from the insidious law that is designed to deprive them of their health and their rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and chief executive of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit seeking to block the law on behalf of three of the five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also involved doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs, and they are also asking for this permission.
Louisiana is among eleven states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional.
Key parts of the Texas bill that would shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Campaigners for women’s rights to abortion, along with the American Obstetricians and Gynecologists Association and the American Medical Association, argue that the need for such a permit places demands on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion objected by saying the measures were aimed at protecting women's health, and some also welcomed the fact that clinics would be closed because of the measures.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one abortion doctor in Louisiana has a permit.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, the doctor would also stop performing the procedure out of fear for his safety, the group said.
Louisiana authorities said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while they wait for the application to be processed.
