Prison Guards Organize Protests in Bulgaria
Hundreds of employees of the prison service throughout Bulgaria participated in a nationwide protest rally in front of the Ministry of Justice in the capital Sofia.
In a peaceful demonstration, they reiterated their demand for the reintroduction of the original working conditions, which have recently changed.
On the list of demands to be discussed with the interim Minister of Justice Hristo Ivanov are also higher salaries.
Peacekeepers for a month symbolically protested the new working hours and demanded a return to the original twenty-four-hour shifts.
Although the prison guards' union and representatives of the Ministry of Justice met, they did not agree, Bulgarian State Radio (BNR) reported.
“Negotiations are still ongoing,” Rosen Zhelyazkov, head of the General Directorate of the Prison Service, told BNR.
Members of the Federation of Workers' Trade Unions in the Ministry of the Interior are also expected to join the protests of prison service employees.
Why the Universe May Have Multiple Dimensions and We Can't See Them
Physicists don't usually write best-sellers, but Brian Greene of Columbia University hit it off in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for laymen to penetrate the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists deal with today - the attempt to unify two great but incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
Undoubtedly, one of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is that the search for a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the basic problem between two key theories (because our universe is currently de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and solve it so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to laymen.
In addition, Greene dealt with the complex material so freshly and engagingly that he can not be blamed for how much interesting he did not include in his book.
In addition, he has largely corrected his "mistake" in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and The Hidden Reality.
Apparently, even the author would not object to his book becoming obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with the ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a little more lively in this area (perhaps due to the fact that the LHC accelerator will finally run on "full gas"), so it is a good time to enter the Greene non-violently open doors of the world of modern physics.
How big can our universe be?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound foolish, fantastic, strange, or mystical.
Yet it is concrete and perfectly acceptable.
To understand this, let’s turn our eyes from the universe as a whole for a moment to something more grounded, namely a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine stretching a 100-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the whole scene from half a kilometer away (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily detect a long, horizontally stretched hose, but if you are not suffering from acuity, you will hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on a hose has only one dimension in which to walk: a left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at a given moment, you only answer with one piece of information: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we're saying is that from a mile away, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose is thick.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is clear that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "clockwise/counterclockwise direction", that is, around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant, you need to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where it is on the circle wrapping the hose.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note that experts note that this chapter focuses purely on the fault theory of strings.
Non-disruptive aspects are discussed in chapters 12 and 13.)
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circumference, marked by a circular arrow, is short and coiled.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The size along the hose is long and easy to see.
The dimensions surrounding the hose circumference are short, "wound" and less noticeable.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important property of spatial dimensions.
That they split into two groups.
They can be either large, large and therefore directly visible, or, conversely, small, coiled and much harder to observe.
Of course, in this case, we did not work hard to reveal the "wound" dimension surrounding the thickness of the hose.
All you had to do was get a pair of binoculars to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - the coiled dimension would only be revealed with great effort.
Kaluza sent Einstein an article in 1919 in which he came up with the astonishing idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three known dimensions.
Kaluza argued that the extra dimension provides an elegant and convincing framework in which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises of how this observation of Kaluza goes together with the obvious fact that we see precisely the three dimensions of space.
The answer Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines, and clearly stated and specified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands or falls with the claim that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and coiled dimensions.
This means that, like dimensions in the direction of hose length, our universe also has large, vast and easily visible three dimensions, the existence of which we are aware of every moment.
But, by analogy with the circular circumference of a garden hose, the universe may also have additional dimensions, tightly coiled into a space so tiny that it has so far remained hidden from our most sophisticated experimental apparatuses.
To get a clearer idea of the nature of Kaluza’s remarkable design, let’s stick to the hose for a moment.
Imagine that on the perimeter of the hose we draw a rather dense row of circles in black.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
Thanks to the drawing, we will now discover the coiled dimension even more easily, as we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but apart from one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imagination a little, note the illustration in Figure 3; it shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of the space, just as we enlarged the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of space from the previous level.
Our universe can have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth level of magnification) if they are coiled into a small enough space; this explains that we have not yet directly observed them.
The square mesh shows the commonly known "big" dimensions, while the circle shows the new, tiny and coiled dimension.
Just like loops of threads in a densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of the usual dimensions - we just drew them only into the intersections in the square mesh.
The background of Figure 4 depicts the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - on such common scales as meters, represented by the side of a small square in a square net.
In each image below, we focus on a small area of the image preceding it; we enlarge it to make it visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see on the first few levels of magnification.
However, if we go further in our search for the microscopic properties of space geometry - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, coiled dimension in the shape of a circle, similar to the loops of thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every point in the direction of large dimensions, much like a hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn the circular dimension only in some regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluza and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of space geometry.
The similarity to the hose is obvious, although we note important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have only drawn two), whereas the hose has a large dimension of only one.
The even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly coiled dimension is extremely miniature, it is much more difficult to recognize it - like the circular circumference of the hose - than to observe the apparent, large and expansive dimensions.
If the size of the extra dimension is small enough, it will actually be revealed beyond the power of our state-of-the-art enlarging tools.
But most importantly, the extra dimension is not just a round bump inside the normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration erroneously suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of three common expansive dimensions.
It is a dimension on the other three dimensions independent as well as being top-down, left-right and front-to-back independent of each other (and perpendicular to each other).
A small enough ant could move in all four dimensions, and we would need four figures to determine its position, in addition to the three usual round-dimensional position; if we count time, then five figures, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
