To our surprise, we find that even though we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluza and Klein’s reasoning shows that this does not preclude the existence of additional coiled dimensions if they are small enough.
The universe can have more dimensions than we can see with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
State-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize the structures of a large billionth of a billionth of a meter.
Smaller coiled dimensions can hardly be observed.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluza's original idea with several ideas from the emerging quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the additional circular dimension could be about one Planck length, a size far beyond the resolution of today's instruments.
Since then, physicists have called the possibility of additional small spatial dimensions Kaluza-Klein theory.
