Putin asks Kiev to start talks with eastern Ukraine on “state sovereignty”
On Sunday, Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded that the Ukrainian government stop fighting separatists in the east of the country and immediately start negotiations on the “state sovereignty” of the breakaway areas.
Its spokesman, Dmitry Peskov, later explained that Putin’s remark was not intended to imply that the separatist-controlled areas of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that their status within Ukraine should be reconsidered in order to give the Russian-speaking area the power to protect its rights and interests.
Putin’s call for the Kiev government to treat the pro-Russian rebels as equals is consistent with an apparent strategy that has followed since the outbreak of the unrest five months ago: Help the separatists occupy the territory and force the Ukrainian government to grant the newly proclaimed Novorossiya de facto independence so that it can ally itself with Russia instead of with the West.
In an interview with state television channel 1, Putin condemned Ukrainian military actions to recapture the eastern areas of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were taken over by separatists in March and April after Moscow annexed the Crimean peninsula belonging to Ukraine on March 18.
The Kremlin and separatists have recently labeled the occupied territory “Novorossia” or “New Russia,” a term that refers to the glorious pre-revolutionary days of the Russian Empire.
The Russian news agency Itar-Tass published Putin’s words that the “prisoner of illusions” is anyone who believes that peace negotiations are on the horizon, as Ukrainian politicians launched campaigns ahead of the October 26 parliamentary elections, while government troops are attacking civilians in separatist-controlled areas.
"In the interest of the people living in these areas, we must immediately start meaningful negotiations, not only on legal matters, but also on the political organization of society and the status of state sovereignty of the south-east of Ukraine," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s allusion to state sovereignty was meant in the context of broader autonomy, which has been under discussion with Kiev’s leadership for several months, to alleviate concerns by Russian-speaking areas about threats to cultural and linguistic rights.
Peskov said that only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions.
This is not a matter for discussion between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, “because this is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal Ukrainian conflict.”
The intervention by the Kremlin spokesman, which was supposed to correct the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks, highlighted the Russian leadership’s approach to solving the separatist insurgency in the east, which is different from the open occupation of Crimea, where most of the two million population originally belonged to ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have much more difficulty annexing Donetsk and Luhansk in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million residents are not Russians, and opinion polls conducted before the conflict showed widespread support for remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy that Russian diplomats discussed in international fora would give regional governments in Ukraine the power to determine their own trade agreements and international relations, effectively giving the Kremlin de facto control over the territory that would link the Russian mainland to Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is home to Russia’s main naval fleet, maritime trading facilities, and historic coastal resorts.
The areas between Rostov and Crimea are also the center of mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko, during his June 7 inaugural address, suggested that Ukraine's lawmakers - after the new election - consider changes to the constitution that would give diverse regions more control over their finances and language status.
But this vision of autonomy differs significantly from that of the Kremlin and the separatists, and Moscow is accused of arming and fomenting violence.
Putin’s latest call for Kiev to treat the separatists as equals followed a further advance by the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks from a previously peaceful area along the Sea of Azov penetrated eastern Ukraine.
The separatists, reinforced by the Russians, have taken control of Novoazovsk with such force that Ukrainian security authorities fear it is a campaign to seize strategic coastal territory as far as Crimea.
This spurred a huge civilian and military effort to fortify Mariupol, a port with metallurgical combinations of 500,000 inhabitants, which lies between Novoazovsk and the narrow gateway to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of European Union leaders in Brussels on Saturday, calling for action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for the past 23 years.
“We are approaching a point of no return,” Poroshenko warned.
There are now thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit has not taken any definitive steps - leaders are calling for additional sanctions against Russia in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukrainian crisis.
Colonel Andriy Lysenko, a spokesman for Ukraine's National Security and Defense Council, told reporters in Kiev on Saturday that Ukrainian troops had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaisk after two columns of Russian armored vehicles and 1,000 military units penetrated the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists.
